<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910220-0111</DOCNO><DOCID>910220-0111.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Chairman of Family   Savings Is Convicted   On 14 Criminal Counts</HL><DATE>02/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Oliver A. Trigg Jr., former chairman ofFamily Savings andamp; Loan Association, was convicted of 14criminal counts of conspiracy, bank fraud, money laundering,tax fraud and false statements related to his 1987 purchaseof control of the Los Angeles thrift.   Federal prosecutors alleged in an indictment handed uplast September that Mr. Trigg while serving as chairman butwithout equity in Family Savings, arranged for Family Savingsto lend $2.5 million to a third party for real estatedevelopment. Nearly half of that money was laundered into Mr.Trigg's personal bank account and used to buy a 51% stake inFamily Savings.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Trigg attracted local media attention in August 1987,when he acquired control of Family, which, with more than$140 million, was one of the nation's largest black-ownedsavings and loans. Family Savings remains in operation andnow is controlled by closely held OFC Inc., based inWashington, D.C.   James Cottle, a former vice president of Los Angeles-basedUnion Bank, was convicted of conspiracy and false statementsfor alleged assistance to Mr. Trigg.</TEXT></DOC>